---
import { CodeBlock } from '../../../../src';
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import TokenList from '../../components/TokenList.astro';

const anatomy = [
  { term: '<code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-color</code>', description: 'oklch(84.30% 0.1500 79.5) — a saturated yellow tuned for visibility against both light and dark surfaces.' },
  { term: '<code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-width</code>', description: '3px — wide enough to remain visible at small element sizes, narrow enough to avoid visual overload.' },
  { term: '<code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-offset</code>', description: '2px — pulls the ring away from the element\'s border so the two never visually merge.' },
  { term: '<code class="gw-code">--focus-text</code>', description: 'Foreground colour for any element that uses a yellow background as its focus surface (rare; used by the focus ring on dark mode where contrast inverts).' },
];
---

<DocsLayout title="Focus" description="The 3px yellow focus ring that signals keyboard focus across every Groundwork component">
  <section class="gw-section">
    <div class="gw-width gw-stack--lg">
      <div class="gw-prose">
        <h1>Focus</h1>
        <p>Every interactive element in Groundwork shows the same focus ring: a 3px yellow outline with a 2px offset, drawn from <code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-color</code>, <code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-width</code>, and <code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-offset</code>. The ring is not optional and is not styleable per component.</p>
        <p>The colour is yellow because it remains highly visible against every surface, ink, and action colour in both modes. Other rings (matching the action colour, for example) fail this check.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="gw-prose">
        <h2>Accessibility</h2>
        <p>The focus ring meets <a class="gw-link" href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/Understanding/focus-visible.html">WCAG 2.4.7 (Focus Visible)</a>. It also satisfies <a class="gw-link" href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/Understanding/focus-appearance.html">WCAG 2.4.11 (Focus Appearance)</a> by being at least 2px thick along its perimeter and contrasting at least 3:1 against both the unfocused element's adjacent pixels and the surrounding background.</p>
        <p>Keyboard testing is part of every component's Playwright suite. If a contribution adds a focusable surface, that surface must show the ring under <code class="gw-code">Tab</code> traversal.</p>
        <p>Do not rely on the focus ring alone to communicate state. Form errors include text describing the problem; disabled buttons set <code class="gw-code">aria-disabled</code>; required fields are labelled. The ring tells the user <em>where</em> they are, not <em>what</em> the element does.</p>
      </div>

      <section class="gw-stack" aria-labelledby="focus-anatomy">
        <h2 id="focus-anatomy">Anatomy</h2>
        <p class="gw-body--sm">The focus ring is composed of three tokens. They appear together everywhere the ring is drawn.</p>
        <TokenList entries={anatomy} />
      </section>

      <section class="gw-stack" aria-labelledby="focus-examples">
        <h2 id="focus-examples">Applied</h2>
        <p class="gw-body--sm">The same ring on Button, Input, and a link. The screenshots are static — tab through any component page to see the live ring respond to keyboard focus.</p>
        <div class="gw-card gw-stack--lg">
          <div class="docs-focus-row">
            <button type="button" class="gw-button docs-focus-applied">Save and continue</button>
            <span class="gw-body--xs">Primary Button with focus ring</span>
          </div>
          <div class="docs-focus-row">
            <button type="button" class="gw-button gw-button--secondary docs-focus-applied">Cancel</button>
            <span class="gw-body--xs">Secondary Button — same ring</span>
          </div>
          <div class="docs-focus-row">
            <input type="text" class="gw-input docs-focus-applied" value="user@example.com" readonly aria-label="Email address" />
            <span class="gw-body--xs">Input — outline pulled outside the 2px medium border</span>
          </div>
          <div class="docs-focus-row">
            <a class="gw-link docs-focus-applied" href="#focus-anatomy">Anchor link</a>
            <span class="gw-body--xs">Inline link</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="gw-stack" aria-labelledby="focus-usage">
        <h2 id="focus-usage">Drawing the focus ring</h2>
        <p class="gw-body--sm">Every component CSS rule that handles focus pulls from the same three tokens. Use <code class="gw-code">outline</code>, not <code class="gw-code">box-shadow</code>, so the ring renders consistently against borders.</p>
        <CodeBlock client:load>{`.my-control:focus-visible {
  outline: var(--focus-ring-width) solid var(--focus-ring-color);
  outline-offset: var(--focus-ring-offset);
}`}</CodeBlock>
      </section>

      <div class="gw-prose">
        <h2>Guidance</h2>
        <h3>Never hide the focus ring</h3>
        <p>Setting <code class="gw-code">outline: none</code> on any focusable element is forbidden. If a custom element needs a different visual treatment, it must still show the 3px yellow ring — restyle the inner element, not the outline.</p>

        <h3>Use <code class="gw-code">:focus-visible</code>, not <code class="gw-code">:focus</code></h3>
        <p>Most components draw the ring with <code class="gw-code">:focus-visible</code> so mouse clicks don't surface a ring the keyboard user didn't ask for. Form fields use plain <code class="gw-code">:focus</code> because text-entry focus is always intentional and the ring confirms which field is active.</p>

        <h3>Apply to the right element</h3>
        <p>For composite controls like RadioGroup and CheckboxGroup, the ring is drawn on the visible item (using <code class="gw-code">:has(input:focus-visible)</code>), not on the hidden native input. The result is that the user sees the ring around the labelled option, which is what they're acting on.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="gw-prose">
        <h2>Related</h2>
        <ul class="gw-list">
          <li><a class="gw-link" href="/styles/colour/#colour-focus">Colour</a> — the <code class="gw-code">--focus-text</code> pairing.</li>
          <li><a class="gw-link" href="/styles/borders/#border-widths">Borders</a> — <code class="gw-code">--focus-ring-width</code> is the same primitive as <code class="gw-code">--border-width-thick</code>.</li>
          <li><a class="gw-link" href="/reference/principles/#accessibility-is-structural">Accessibility is structural</a> — why the ring is a system-wide commitment, not a per-component choice.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>

<style>
  .docs-focus-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }

  .docs-focus-applied {
    outline: var(--focus-ring-width) solid var(--focus-ring-color);
    outline-offset: var(--focus-ring-offset);
  }
</style>
